        "id": "static-003",
        "title": "Emotion Neuroscience",
        "content": "## Top 3 Research Groups Focusing on Emotion (fMRI & Computational Models)\n\n1. **Interdisciplinary Affective Science Lab (IASL)** – *Lead PI:* **Lisa Feldman Barrett**, Northeastern University (with a site at MGH). The IASL is internationally known for its research on the nature of emotion, especially the theory of “constructed emotion.” Barrett’s team uses **fMRI** and other measures to study how the brain creates emotional experiences from more fundamental psychological operations. Their widely cited meta-analytic work (e.g. Barrett & colleagues in *Behav. Brain Sci.* 2012) showed that discrete emotions do not localize to singular brain regions; instead, emotions emerge from distributed networks engaging core affect, conceptualization, etc.. Notable publications include *“The brain basis of emotion: a meta-analytic review”* (2012) and theoretical papers proposing that the brain actively predicts and constructs emotional states. **Lab Website:** *IASL, Northeastern University* (affective-science.org).\n\n2. **Emotion & Social Cognition Lab (Adolphs Lab)** – *Lead PI:* **Ralph Adolphs**, California Institute of Technology. Adolphs is a prominent figure in affective neuroscience, known for integrating **fMRI**, lesion studies, and computational approaches to understand emotion and social behavior. His lab investigates how we recognize and experience emotions (e.g. fear, empathy) and how emotion influences decisions and memories. Adolphs’ group has published in top-tier venues (e.g. a landmark *Cell* 2014 review on cross-species emotion frameworks) and authored *The Neuroscience of Emotion: A New Synthesis* (2018). They are widely cited for discoveries like the role of the amygdala in fear perception and for studies linking distributed brain networks to social-emotional behaviors. **Lab Website:** *Emotion & Social Cognition Lab, Caltech* (emotion.caltech.edu).\n\n3. **Dolan Lab / Wellcome Centre for Human Neuroimaging** – *Lead PI:* **Raymond J. Dolan**, University College London (UCL) & Max Planck UCL Centre for Computational Psychiatry. Prof. Dolan’s group is internationally recognized for cutting-edge research on the neurobiology of emotion and decision-making. They pioneered **model-based fMRI**, combining computational models (e.g. reinforcement learning, Bayesian models) with brain imaging to understand how emotional states arise and guide choices. For example, a notable *PNAS* study modeled how reward prediction errors influence momentary happiness and linked this to activity in the striatum. Dolan (elected FRS) is among the world’s most influential neuroscientists, with numerous high-impact papers in *Nature* and *Science*. His lab’s work on fear, reward, and affective valuation – often in collaboration with computational experts (e.g. Peter Dayan) – has greatly advanced our understanding of emotion through computational neuroscience. **Lab Website:** *Max Planck UCL Centre – Dolan Profile* (UCL Computational Psychiatry Centre).\n\n## Key Review Papers on the Neuroscience of Emotion (fMRI and Computational Emphasis)\n\n* **Dalgleish, T. (2004). “The Emotional Brain.” *Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 5*(7): 583–589.** – A seminal overview outlining fundamental questions of affective neuroscience. This highly cited paper reviews which brain systems underlie emotions, whether different emotions map to distinct circuits or shared circuitry, how emotions interact with bodily responses, and how emotion interfaces with cognition and behavior. It provides a historical foundation for newcomers to the field.\n\n* **Lindquist, K.A. et al. (2012). “The brain basis of emotion: a meta-analytic review.” *Behav. Brain Sci., 35*(3): 121–143.** – An influential meta-analysis of **fMRI** studies on human emotion. This paper compared “basic emotion” theories (discrete categories in specific regions) vs. “psychological construction” theories. The findings revealed little evidence for one-to-one mappings of specific emotions to singular brain areas; instead, emotions arise from networks of regions (e.g. salience, default mode networks) that are activated across many emotional states. This review (widely cited) supports the view that brain activity underlying emotions is highly distributed and context-dependent.\n\n* **Barrett, L.F. & Satpute, A.B. (2019). “Historical pitfalls and new directions in the neuroscience of emotion.” *Neuroscience Letters, 693*: 9–18.** – A concise, modern review that critiques past approaches and outlines a **new framework** for emotion research. Barrett and Satpute summarize a century of emotion research and then propose six key directions grounded in a multi-level predictive coding account of emotion. Notably, they argue emotions are not reactive states but are actively constructed by the brain’s predictions (based on context and interoceptive signals). This paper is a useful introduction to contemporary theories integrating **active inference** and computational models into affective neuroscience.\n\n* **Malezieux, M., Klein, A.S., & Gogolla, N. (2023). “Neural Circuits for Emotion.” *Annual Review of Neuroscience, 46*: 211–231.** – A recent comprehensive review emphasizing cross-species findings and circuit mechanisms of emotion. It discusses how emotions can be defined from an evolutionary perspective and studied in both humans and animal models. The authors review neural circuit mechanisms underlying emotion processing across species, highlighting points of convergence (e.g. conserved pathways for positive vs. negative valence) and the modern tools used to dissect these circuits. This up-to-date article is valuable for understanding how human fMRI results align with optogenetic and electrophysiological studies in animals, bridging human and computational/animal research.\n\n* **Lee, K. et al. (2021). “Predictive processing models and affective neuroscience.” *Neurosci. Biobehav. Rev., 131*: 211–228.** – (For further reading) A recent review focusing on **computational modeling** in emotion research. It examines how predictive processing (a computational framework) can explain emotion-related brain function. The paper critiques standard fMRI approaches and illustrates how *active inference* and predictive models provide new insights into affective brain processes. This review connects psychological theory with neuroimaging findings, making it a high-quality resource on the emerging computational perspective in affective neuroscience.\n\n**Sources:**\n\n* Barrett Lab – *Interdisciplinary Affective Science* (lab website); Barrett et al. 2012 (BBS meta-analysis)\n* Adolphs Lab – *Emotion & Social Cognition* (lab website); Anderson & Adolphs 2014 (*Cell* review)\n* Ray Dolan Profile – UCL/Max Planck Centre; Rutledge et al. 2014 (*PNAS* computational model of happiness)\n* Dalgleish 2004 (*Nat. Rev. Neurosci.*); Lindquist et al. 2012; Barrett & Satpute 2019; Malezieux et al. 2023.",
